    <p class="letter-text">My first trip to Eastern Europe started almost by accident. A friend who had been backpacking through the Czech Republic wouldn't stop talking about Prague â€” the architecture, the beer, the sense of stepping back in time. I booked a flight and haven't stopped exploring the region since.<br><br>What I found in Eastern Europe was something most Western travel sites completely miss. These countries aren't "undiscovered" â€” they have centuries of history, world-class cuisine, and cities that rival anything in Western Europe at a fraction of the cost. <strong>But the travel information available was either outdated, superficial, or written by someone who spent three days there on a press trip.</strong><br><br>Over the years, I've walked the cobblestone streets of Krakow's Old Town, watched the sun set over Dubrovnik's city walls, soaked in Budapest's thermal baths, explored Tallinn's medieval quarter, and eaten my way through the markets of Ljubljana. Each trip deepened my appreciation for a part of Europe that deserves far more attention than it gets.<br><br>Eastern Europe rewards the curious traveler â€” the one willing to take the local tram instead of the tour bus, eat at the neighborhood restaurant instead of the tourist trap, and stay long enough to feel the rhythm of a city. <strong>That's the kind of travel this site is built for.</strong> I want you to experience these places the way I do â€” not the Instagram version, but the real one.</p>
